  "prompt": "Does a white background use more energy on a LCD than if it was set to black?",
  "response": "Yes, a white background generally consumes more energy on an LCD screen compared to a black background. This is primarily due to how LCD technology works. In an LCD display, each pixel is made up of liquid crystals that are lit from behind by a backlight. When displaying white, the crystals allow more light to pass through, which requires the backlight to be brighter. Conversely, displaying black generally means the crystals block more light, allowing the backlight to dim slightly or remain at its baseline intensity. This difference in the amount of light passing through the screen translates to higher energy consumption for white backgrounds compared to black ones.",
